<subsection xml:id="subsec-simp_pendulum">
  <title>Simple Pendulum</title>

  <figure xml:id="sp1a">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="sp1a.png" width="40%"/>
  </figure>
  <p>
    A simple pendulum consists of a heavy bob of mass <m>m</m>  hanging from an 
    inextensible and massless string of length <m>l.</m> When the bob is displaced 
    from its mean position and released, it will swing back and forth with periodic 
    motion as shown in <xref ref="sp1a"/>. From free body diagram, it is clear that 
   <m>mg\cos\theta </m> is balanced by tension <m>T</m> in the string but unbalanced 
   force <m>mg\sin\theta </m> provides the restoring force. Hence 
   <me>
    F_{s} = -mg\sin\theta 
   </me>
   <me>
    \text{or,}\quad ma = -mg\frac{x}{l}
   </me>
   <me>
    \text{or,}\quad a = -\frac{g}{l}x =-\omega^{2}x 
   </me>
   where <m>\omega = \sqrt{\frac{g}{l}} </m> is the angular velocity of the 
   bob performing circular motion. The time period of simple pendulum can be given as 
   <me>
    \omega = \frac{2\pi}{T}=\sqrt{\frac{g}{l}} 
   </me>
   <me>
    \therefore \quad T = 2\pi\sqrt{\frac{l}{g}} 
   </me>
     </p>
     <p>
      <term>Alternative:</term>
The restoring torque <xref ref="subsec-rot_overview"/> acting on the bob is given by 
<me>
  \tau=-mgl\sin\theta 
</me>
<me>
  or, \, I \alpha =ml^{2}\frac{\,d\omega}{\,dt}= ml^{2}\ddot{\theta}
</me>
As a restoring torque is giving a clockwise rotation when angular displacement is counterclockwise.
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad ml^{2}\ddot{\theta} =-mgl\sin\theta 
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad l\ddot{\theta} =-g\sin\theta =-g\theta \qquad [\text{small angle approximation}]
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad \ddot{\theta}+\frac{g}{l}\theta= 0 
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad \ddot{\theta}+\omega^{2}\theta = 0  \qquad   \left[\omega = \sqrt{\frac{g}{l}}\right] 
</me>
This is second order differential equation the solution of which can be written as 
<me>
  \theta(t) = \Theta(\sin\omega t + \phi)
</me>
where <m>\Theta</m> is called an angular amplitude. 
     </p>
</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-comp_pendulum">
  <title>Compound Pendulum</title>

  <figure xml:id="cp1">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="cp1.png" width="40%"/>
  </figure>
  <p>
    A compound pendulum consists of a rigid body that oscillates about a horizontal 
    frictionless axis passing through a point <m>S</m>. It is also called a physical 
    pendulum. When a body is displaced from its equilibrium position by an angle <m>\theta,</m> 
    then the restoring torque starts acting on the center of gravity G of the body which is given by 
    <me>
      \tau = I \alpha = -mga\sin\theta
    </me>
    <me>
      \text{or,}\quad I\ddot{\theta}=-mga\theta \quad [\text{for small angle approximation}]
    </me>
    <me>
      \text{or,}\quad \ddot{\theta}+\frac{mga}{I}\theta =0
    </me>
    <me>
      \text{or,}\quad \ddot{\theta}+\omega^{2}\theta =0
    </me>
    where <m>\omega^{2}=\frac{mga}{I} </m>
    <me>
      or, \, \omega = \sqrt{\frac{mga}{I}} =\frac{2\pi}{T} 
    </me>
    <me>
      \therefore\quad T = \sqrt{\frac{I}{mga}} 
    </me>
    here, 
    <me>
       I = I_{cm}+Ma^{2} = Mk^{2}+Ma^{2} 
    </me>
    <m>k</m> is radius of gyration
    <me>
      \therefore\quad T = 2\pi\sqrt{\frac{k^{2}+a^{2}}{ga}}
    </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Comparing time period of simple pendulum and compound pendulums we will get -
        <me>
          l=\frac{k^{2}+a^{2}}{a}
        </me>
        This is the length of equivalent simple pendulum.  If all the mass of a 
        rigid body were concentrated at a point <m>O</m> [<xref ref="cp1"/>] 
        such that 
        <me>
          SO= \frac{k^{2}+a^{2}}{a}
        </me>
          then we will get a simple pendulum of same time period. The point <m>O</m> is called 
          the <em>center of oscillation</em>. Now from <me>
            l=\frac{k^{2}+a^{2}}{a},
          </me>
           we have -
           <me>
            a^{2}-la+k^{2} =0
           </me>
           Which is a quadratic in a, whose roots are 
           <me>
            a=\frac{l\pm\sqrt{l^{2}-4k^{2}}}{2}
           </me>
           Therefore 
           <me>
            a_{1} +a_{2} =l
           </me>
          and 
          <me>
            a_{1}a_{2}=k^{2}
          </me>
          Thus both <m>a_{1}</m> and <m>a_{2}</m> are positive. That is there are 
          two positions of the center of suspension and center of oscillation about 
          which the time periods are the same.  The distance between two such positions 
          of the centers of suspension, asymmetrically located on either side of C.G, 
          is the length <m>l=a+b</m> of the simple equivalent pendulum. Thus time period 
          through point <m>S</m> or <m>O</m> is same. If the body is supported by an 
          axis through <m>G</m>, the time period of oscillation would be infinite. 
      </p>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-largeangl_approx">
  <title>Simple Pendulum with Large Angle Approximation</title>

  <figure xml:id="spelliptical">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="spelliptical.png" width="40%"/>
  </figure>
  <p>
    <me>
      x=l\theta
    </me>
    <me>
      \text{or,}\quad \dot{x} =l\dot{\theta} 
    </me>
    <me>
      V =-mgl\cos\theta
    </me>
    <me>
      K=\frac{1}{2}m\dot{x}^{2} = \frac{1}{2}ml^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2} 
    </me>
    <me>
      T=K+V = \frac{1}{2}ml^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}-mgl\cos\theta =const. 
    </me>
    <me>
      \text{Now,}\quad \frac{\,dT}{\,dt} =0 =\frac{1}{2}ml^{2}2\dot{\theta}\ddot{\theta}+mgl\sin\theta\dot{\theta}
    </me>
    <me>
      \text{and}\quad \dot{\theta}\ddot{\theta} =-\frac{g}{l}\sin\theta\dot{\theta}  \qquad [\because \theta \quad \text{is large}]
    </me>
      <me>
  \text{or,}\quad \frac{\,d\theta}{\,dt}\left[\frac{\,d}{\,dt}\left(\frac{\,d\theta}{\,dt}\right)\right] =-\frac{g}{l}\sin\theta\left(\frac{\,d\theta}{\,dt}\right) 
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad \frac{\,d\theta}{\,dt}\left[\,d\left(\frac{\,d\theta}{\,dt}\right)\right] =-\frac{g}{l}\sin\theta\,d\theta 
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad \int\dot{\theta}\left(\,d\dot{\theta}\right) =-\frac{g}{l}\int\sin\theta\,d\theta
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad \frac{\dot{\theta}^{2}}{2}=\frac{g}{l}cos\theta+k. \qquad [\text{where k is a constant.}]
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-larg_sp1">
  \text{or,}\quad \frac{\dot{\theta}^{2}}{2}-\omega^{2}cos\theta=k. \qquad \left[\because \omega=\sqrt{\frac{g}{l}}\right]
</men>
This is a non-linear differential equation. At first extremum, <m>\theta \to \theta_{i},</m> 
and angular velocity at that moment is <m>\dot{\theta}_{i}=0</m> where <m>i</m> 
stands for maximum value of <m>\theta.</m>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad 0 = \omega^{2}cos\theta_{i}+k
</me>
<me>
  \therefore\quad k = -\omega^{2}cos\theta_{i}
</me>
Therefore eqn. <xref ref="eqn-larg_sp1"/> becomes -
<me>
  \frac{\dot{\theta}^{2}}{2}=\omega^{2}cos\theta-\omega^{2}cos\theta_{i}
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad \dot{\theta} = \omega\sqrt{2\left(\cos\theta-\cos\theta_{i}\right)} 
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad \frac{\,d\theta}{\,dt} = \omega \sqrt{2\left(\cos\theta-\cos\theta_{i}\right)}
</me>
At mean position at <m>t=0,\theta=0,</m> and <m>\dot{\theta} \gt 0.</m>
<me>
  \therefore\quad \int\limits_{0}^{t} \omega\,dt =\int\limits_{0}^{\theta_{i}}  \frac{\,d\theta}{\sqrt{2\left(\cos\theta-\cos\theta_{i}\right)}} 
</me>
Here, 
<me>
  \left(\cos\theta-\cos\theta_{i}\right) =1-2\sin^{2}\frac{\theta}{2} - 1+2\sin^{2}\frac{\theta_{i}}{2} 
</me>
<me>
  = 2\left(\sin^{2}\frac{\theta_{i}}{2} -\sin^{2}\frac{\theta}{2}\right) 
</me>
<me>
  \therefore\quad  \omega t =\frac{1}{2}\int\limits_{0}^{\theta_{i}}  \frac{\,d\theta}{\sqrt{\left(\sin^{2}\frac{\theta_{i}}{2} -\sin^{2}\frac{\theta}{2}\right)}} 
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-larg_sp2">
  = \frac{1}{2}\int\limits_{0}^{\theta_{i}}  \frac{\,d\theta}{\sin\frac{\theta_{i}}{2} \sqrt{\left( 1-\frac{\sin^{2}\frac{\theta}{2}}{\sin^{2}\frac{\theta_{i}}{2}}\right)}}  
</men>
Set 
<me>
  \sin\phi= \frac{\sin\frac{\theta}{2}}{\sin\frac{\theta_{i}}{2}}
</me>
<me>
  \text{and say}\quad  \sin\frac{\theta_{i}}{2} =b 
</me>

 and <m> \sin\phi</m> oscillates between <m>-1 \quad\text{to}\quad  +1.</m>
Now, 
<men xml:id="eqn-larg_sp3">
  \sin\frac{\theta}{2} = b\sin\phi 
</men>
<men xml:id="eqn-larg_sp4">
  \therefore \quad \omega t= \frac{1}{2}\int \frac{\,d\theta}{b \sqrt{ 1-\sin^{2}\phi}} = \frac{1}{2}\int \frac{\,d\theta}{b \cos\phi} 
</men>
Differentiating eqn. <xref ref="eqn-larg_sp3"/>, we get -
<me>
  \sin\frac{\theta}{2} =b\sin\phi
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad \frac{1}{2} \cos\frac{\theta}{2}\,d\theta = b\cos\phi\,d\phi
</me>
<me>
  \text{or,}\quad \,d\theta = \frac{2b\cos\phi\,d\phi}{\cos\frac{\theta}{2}}
</me>
From eqn. <xref ref="eqn-larg_sp4"/>, we have -
<me>
  \omega t = \frac{1}{2}\int \frac{2b\cos\phi\,d\phi}{\cos\frac{\theta}{2}b\cos\phi}
</me>
<me>
  = \int \frac{\,d\phi}{\cos\frac{\theta}{2}} = \int \frac{\,d\phi}{1-\sin^{2}\frac{\theta}{2}}
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-larg_sp5">
  \therefore\quad \omega t  = \int \frac{\,d\phi}{1-b^{2}\sin^{2}\phi}  
</men>
This a first kind of elliptical integral.
      </p>
      <p>
From power series, 
<me>
  \left(1-b^{2}\sin^{2}\phi\right)^{-\frac{1}{2}} = 1+\frac{1}{2}b^{2}\sin^{2}\phi+\frac{3}{2^{3}}b^{4}\sin^{4}\phi+\cdots
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-larg_sp6">
  \therefore\quad \omega t = \int \left[1+\frac{1}{2}b^{2}\sin^{2}\phi+\frac{3}{8}b^{4}\sin^{4}\phi+\cdots\right]\,d\phi  
</men>
At <m>t=0, \,\theta=0,</m> the swing is at the lowest point, and hence <m>\sin\phi=0</m> 
<m>\Rightarrow \phi=0</m> see eqn.<xref ref="eqn-larg_sp3"/>.
Hence, from eqn. <xref ref="eqn-larg_sp6"/>, 
<me>
  \omega T_{1} = \int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}\,d\phi =2\pi
</me>
<me>
  \omega T_{2} = \int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}\frac{b^{2}}{2}\sin^{2}\phi\,d\phi 
</me>
<me>
  =\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}\frac{b^{2}}{2}\frac{\left(1-\cos2\phi\right)}{2}\,d\phi 
</me>
<me>
  = \frac{b^{2}}{2}\pi = \frac{1}{2}\pi\sin^{2}\frac{\theta_{i}}{2} 
</me>
<me>
  \omega T = 2\pi+\frac{\pi}{2}\sin^{2}\frac{\theta_{i}}{2} +\cdots 
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-larg_sp7">
  \therefore\quad T = 2\pi\sqrt{\frac{l}{g}}\left[1+\frac{1}{4}\sin^{2}\frac{\theta_{i}}{2}+\cdots \right]
</men>
      </p>
</subsection>
